{"id":"2011.04059","submitter":"Ramon van Handel","authors":"Yair Shenfeld and Ramon van Handel","title":"The Extremals of the Alexandrov-Fenchel Inequality for Convex Polytopes","comments":"82 pages, 4 figures; final version","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.MG math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Alexandrov-Fenchel inequality, a far-reaching generalization of the\nclassical isoperimetric inequality to arbitrary mixed volumes, lies at the\nheart of convex geometry. The characterization of its extremal bodies is a\nlong-standing open problem that dates back to Alexandrov's original 1937 paper.\nThe known extremals already form a very rich family, and even the fundamental\nconjectures on their general structure, due to Schneider, are incomplete. In\nthis paper, we completely settle the extremals of the Alexandrov-Fenchel\ninequality for convex polytopes. In particular, we show that the extremals\narise from the combination of three distinct mechanisms: translation, support,\nand dimensionality. The characterization of these mechanisms requires the\ndevelopment of a diverse range of techniques that shed new light on the\ngeometry of mixed volumes of nonsmooth convex bodies. Our main result extends\nfurther beyond polytopes in a number of ways, including to the setting of\nquermassintegrals of arbitrary convex bodies. As an application of our main\nresult, we settle a question of Stanley on the extremal behavior of certain\nlog-concave sequences that arise in the combinatorics of partially ordered\nsets.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 8 Nov 2020 19:12:59 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 2 Feb 2022 19:35:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-04"}
{"id":"2011.04060","submitter":"Richard Lyon","authors":"Richard F. Lyon","title":"Closed-form Tight Bounds and Approximations for the Median of a Gamma\n  Distribution","comments":"20 pages, 9 figures; submitted to Constructive Approximation","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1371/journal.pone.0251626","report-no":null,"categories":"math.FA math.PR","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  We show how to find upper and lower bounds to the median of a gamma\ndistribution, over the entire range of shape parameter $k > 0$, that are the\ntightest possible bounds of the form $2^{-1/k} (A + Bk)$, with closed-form\nparameters $A$ and $B$. The lower bound of this form that is best at high $k$\nstays between 48 and 50 percentile, while the uniquely best upper bound stays\nbetween 50 and 55 percentile. We show how to form even tighter bounds by\ninterpolating between these bounds, yielding closed-form expressions that more\ntightly bound the median. Good closed-form approximations between the bounds\nare also found, including one that is exact at $k = 1$ and stays between 49.97\nand 50.03 percentile.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 8 Nov 2020 19:28:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-09"}
